No, that would be digital bandwidth. Baud rate is the number of symbols per unit of time, but in modern networks, for example, each symbol can have several states, so it may represent several bit sequences, making bps-to-baud kinda difficult.

The alien signal may not even use the same symbols and encoding terran modems and such use, but since it's a radio signal, I endeavor it's a sine wave, and uses the same 1 start, 8 data, 0 parity, 1 stop bit configuration as modems. If so, a 10TB/s bandwidth would be something like 8.58994x10^13 baud (10TB/sX1024X1024X1024X8X100), which is pretty damn high, IMHO…

Since I'm not a telco-expert either, could someone who is (if there's anyone here) double-check my work? I think my math is sound, but just to be sure…

Also, if the good Doctor released some more info on the signal, I might be able to come up with a better approximation to something that's scary fast enough.





