Right. I like this one. Few possible solutions to Bright's issues.

1) Move it. Put it somewhere away from Earth, but still collecting data. After all, who's to say that alien technology requires that kind of proximity? I like Jovian orbit, myself. It's out of easy reach. It also makes the thing more out there, since our technology couldn't detect the things it's picking up from that range. It also hints a bit more of the things the Foundation is capable of; how else could they even find the satellite that far away?

2) Don't have the Foundation grab it or destroy it. I can easily see the Foundation deciding to leave it where it is. Instead, they figure out how it works well enough to start feeding it false data. This shows that the Foundation is doing something about it, while leaving it where it is. Possibly hint that the Foundation is uncertain whether or not they're giving data that serves the needs of Earth or not (we say we have more nukes; does it deter them, or make them see us as a threat? We say we have fewer nukes; do they decide we're not worth bothering, or that we're weak enough to attack?).





