Did you…if that's not a load of technobabble I'll eat my hat. 2000 gigawatts is far, far beyond anything we can make today, or in the foreseeable future. The HELLADS (High Energy Liquid Laser Area Defence System) device is designed to kill incoming artillery, and it runs on 150 kilowatts. The YAL-1 system, mounted on a modified Boeing 747 is the only megawatt-class reference I could find, and it's massive and not viable. For comparison, the United States draws (if I calculated this correctly) 442582Mw per year. A 2000-Mw laser is not only overkill for a satellite (we've got satellite kill weapons, the American ASM-135, modifications to the RIM-161 SM3, and other models, notably from China and Russia), but almost impossible without immense amounts of fuel and possibly a small nuclear reactor.





